Title:
A Technical Deep Dive: Comparing Anti-Cheat Bypass and EDR Bypass

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post compares anti-cheat bypass techniques used to evade game integrity controls with EDR bypass techniques used to evade endpoint detection in enterprise environments.  
- It frames the different goals, motivations, impacts, and legal/ethical boundaries between cheating ecosystems and malware/attacker tradecraft, while noting overlap in underlying methods.  
- The article highlights common Windows user-mode primitives used in both domains (e.g., remote thread injection and memory allocation/writes) and contrasts them with EDR-centric tactics like persistence, privilege manipulation, and anti-analysis.  
- It provides illustrative code snippets for DLL injection, function hooking (Detours-style), packet manipulation, and obfuscation, then discusses EDR evasion concepts such as polymorphism, rootkit-style hiding, encoded shellcode, string obfuscation, and anti-debugging.  
- A small demo section shows how XOR-based API name obfuscation and runtime resolution (GetModuleHandle/GetProcAddress) can reduce obvious static indicators in a malicious DLL (referencing a Notepad++ DLL sideloading scenario).  
- Useful for red teamers and malware analysts as a conceptual mapping between anti-cheat and EDR evasion tradecraft, and for blue teamers to understand shared primitives and detection opportunities.

Technical Focus:
- Windows process injection (CreateRemoteThread, VirtualAllocEx, WriteProcessMemory, LoadLibrary)
- API hooking / detouring and user-mode manipulation
- Obfuscation & polymorphism (junk code, XOR string/API obfuscation, runtime API resolution)
- Anti-analysis / anti-debugging (IsDebuggerPresent, conditional logic)
- Kernel/rootkit concepts (NtQuerySystemInformation tampering) and hiding artifacts
- Persistence and privilege/token manipulation (registry/services, AdjustTokenPrivileges)

Use Cases:
- Map anti-cheat bypass primitives to EDR evasion patterns for threat modeling
- Build detection logic around common injection and runtime API-resolution behaviors
- Improve static analysis by recognizing XORed strings and delayed API imports
- Red team tradecraft education: comparing gaming vs enterprise defensive stacks
- Defensive research: identify telemetry points for injection, hooking, and obfuscation

Keywords:
anti-cheat, EDR bypass, DLL injection, CreateRemoteThread, VirtualAllocEx, WriteProcessMemory, LoadLibraryA, GetProcAddress, GetModuleHandle, API hooking, Detours, packet manipulation, polymorphic malware, string obfuscation, XOR, shellcode encoding, anti-debugging, IsDebuggerPresent, NtQuerySystemInformation, rootkit, DLL sideloading, Notepad++ v8.5.4